","Easby, Yorkshire, Inglaterra, Reino Unido":"Easby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Albini","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Antonio, Pasquale, Aldo, Amalio, Americo, Armando, Carlo, Caterina, Claudio, Gino, Mario, Maurizio, Nichola, Nicola, Severino, Vittorio.","Italian:","patronymic or plural form of   Albino  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Albino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Ramon, Manuel, Ana, Carlos, Julio, Luis, Raul, Ruben, Alfonso, Andres, Angel.  Italian Pasquale, Angelo, Antonio, Carmine, Giovanni, Luigi, Sal, Santo, Saverio, Ubalda.","Portuguese, Spanish, and southern Italian:","from the personal name <i>Albino</i> (see   Albin  )."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mowbray","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern; of Norman origin): habitational name from Montbray (Manche). Robert <i>de Mowbray</i> was Earl of Northumbria 1086–95, but was later imprisoned and deposed for rebelling against William II."],"variants":[{"name":"Mulberry","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Cambridgeshire): variant of   Mowbray  .","Irish (Derry): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoilbhearaigh</b> ‘descendant of the devotee of (Saint) <i>Bearach</i>’."]},{"name":"Moubray","meanings":["English: variant of   Mowbray  ."]},{"name":"Mayberry","meanings":["English: most probably an altered form of   Mowbray  . It is also found as   Maybury  , which has the form of an English habitational name. There is a place near Woking in Surrey so called; however, this is not recorded until 1885 and is probably derived from the surname. In England this surname is found mainly in the West Midlands; it has also spread into Wales. In Ireland this form is common in Ulster; MacLysaght records that it was taken there from England in the 17th century."]},{"name":"Memory","meanings":["English: variant of   Mowbray  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Albini de Mowbray was born about 1180, in Easby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Albini de Mowbray, was 34 and his mother, Mabel Fitzpatric, was 32. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. William Mowbray. He died in 1234, in his hometown, at the age of 55."},"et":{"aproximadamente 1180–1234":"umbes 1180–1234","1180–1234":"1180–1234","1184–Female":"1184–Surnud","1210–1252":"1210–1252","1148–1191":"1148–1191","1150–1203":"1150–1